.IX Title "HDB_GET_ROOT 1"
.TH HDB_GET_ROOT 1 "2006-03-29" "Wed Apr  5 13:07:17 EDT 2006" "HDB API Documenation"
.SH "NAME"
hdb_get_root, hhdb_get_root, hdb_set_root, hhdb_set_root
.SH "LIBRARY"
.IX Header "LIBRARY"
hdb C Library (libhdb, \-lhdb, libnhdb, \-lnhdb)
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
\&\fB#include <hdb.h\fR>
.PP
\&\fBchar *\f(BIhdb_get_root()\fB;\fR
.PP
\&\fBchar *hhdb_get_root(\s-1HDB\s0 *hdbp);\fR
.PP
\&\fBint hdb_set_root(const char *root);\fR
.PP
\&\fBint hhdb_set_root(\s-1HDB\s0 *hdbp, const char *root);\fR
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
The \fIhdb_get_root()\fR family of functions changes underlying directory where \s-1HDB\s0 saves it's databases. The default \s-1HDB\s0 root is /var/db/hdb. Use libnhdb for network enabled hdb access and libhdb for file based access. Network calls need a running hdbd daemon.
.PP
hdb_set_root will only set valid root directories. A valid root directory must contain the string \*(L"hdb\*(R", must not contain 
\&\*(L"..\*(R" or \*(L";\*(R" and must not begin with \*(L"~\*(R" or \*(L".\*(R". If the underlying root directory doesn't exist it will be created.
.PP
hdb_get_root returns the current root. Default root is /var/db/hdb/
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.IX Header "EXAMPLES"
Set a new root the fetch the current root:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        int errcode = 0;
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 4
\&        if((errcode = hdb_set_root("/home/hampa/hdb")) != 0){
\&                fprintf(stderr, "Unable to set root error %i\en", errcode);
\&        }
\&        printf("HDBROOT directory is %s\en", hdb_get_root());
.Ve
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.IX Header "EXIT STATUS"
Functions returns a zero exist status on success. see \fIhdb_errors\fR\|(3) for possible \s-1HDB\s0 error codes.
.SH "ENVIRONMENT"
.IX Header "ENVIRONMENT"
\&\s-1HDBROOT\s0 
        default root can be set with \s-1HDBROOT\s0 enviroment variable. 
